      </h1>
      <h2>Introduction</h2>
      <p>
        Have you ever been told to add salt to the water to help it to heat
        faster? Or noticed that the time it takes to heat water varies with the
        amount of water you are heating?
      </p>
      <p>
        These ideas may seem basic but are the basis of this IA and the idea of
        specific heat capacity. The heat capacity of an object is defined as the
        amount of thermal energy required to increase that object's temperature
        by 1 K (Khan Academy 2021). However, this measurement isn't particularly
        useful because if the amount (mass, volume or moles) of that object
        changes, the heat capacity must be recalculated. The concept of specific
        heat capacity is founded on the assumption that the amount of a
        substance is directly proportional to its heat capacity. Using this
        assumption, specific heat capacity can be defined as the amount of
        thermal energy required to heat one amount unit (1 kilogram, 1 mole, 1
        metre cubed) of a substance by 1 K (Tsokos 2014). Most commonly, and
        throughout this IA, specific heat capacity refers to the amount of
        thermal energy required to heat 1 kg of a substance by 1 K.
      </p>
      <p>
        After studying specific heat capacity in class, I found myself
        unsatisfied with not knowing why specific heat capacity varies between
        substances. To understand why the specific heat capacity varies between
        substances, it is first helpful to investigate the concept of
        temperature. Temperature is directly proportional to the average random
        kinetic energy within an object (Tsokos 2014). Since this
        proportionality is so strict, it can be said that any other store of
        energy that isn't random kinetic will increase the specific heat
        capacity. This introduces many factors that can affect specific heat
        capacity, such as chemical bonds. One such factor that, according to
        Richard Feynman, is particularly important, is the number of 'degrees of
        freedom' a given molecule has. Each degree of freedom represents a
        parameter that is required to describe the motion of a molecule
        (LibreTexts 2017). Only some of the energy used to heat a substance will
        go toward degrees of freedom that increase the temperature, and the
        number of degrees of freedom varies between molecules.
      </p>
      <p>
        To investigate specific heat capacity further, I decided to explore
        sodium chloride dissolved in water. I decided to investigate it at
        different concentrations, which led me to my research question:
      </p>
      <p class="italic font-bold">
        How does the mass of sodium chloride dissolved in water affect the
        specific heat capacity of the solution?
      </p>
      <p>
        This experiment will involve finding the specific heat capacity of
        different sodium chloride solutions.
      </p>
      <p>The specific heat capacity formula is the following:</p>
      <h3 class="text-gray-600 text-sm">Equation 1</h3>
      <Math
        latex={String.raw`Q=mc \Delta T`}
        whereList={[
          {
            propertyAsLatex: "Q",
            value: "Energy in",
            unitAsLatex: "J",
          },
          {
            propertyAsLatex: "m",
            value: "Mass of substance in",
            unitAsLatex: "kg",
          },
          {
            propertyAsLatex: "c",
            value: "Specific heat capacity in",
            unitAsLatex: String.raw`J\cdot kg^{-1}\cdot K^{-1}`,
          },
        ]}
      />
      <p>It can be rearranged to find the specific heat capacity:</p>
      <h3 class="text-gray-600 text-sm">Equation 2</h3>
      <Math latex={String.raw`c=\frac{Q}{m \Delta T}`} />
      <p>
        In this experiment, a sodium chloride solution is heated and then mixed
        with a substance of known mass and heat capacity. The energy transfer to
        the substance of known mass and heat capacity is calculated using
        equation 1. The mass, temperature change of sodium chloride solution and
        calculated energy transfer is substituted into equation 2 to give the
        specific heat capacity of the sodium chloride solution. Equation 3
        represents this in a single equation.
      </p>
      <h3 class="text-gray-600 text-sm">Equation 3</h3>
      <Math
        latex={String.raw`c_{s}\ =\ \frac{m_{w}c_{w} \Delta T_{w}}{m_{s} \Delta T_{s}}`}
        whereList={[
          {
            propertyAsLatex: String.raw`c_{s}`,
            value: "Specific heat capacity of solution in",
            unitAsLatex: String.raw`J\cdot kg^{-1}\cdot K^{-1}`,
          },
          {
            propertyAsLatex: String.raw`m_{w}`,
            value: "Mass of the substance of known specific heat capacity in",
            unitAsLatex: String.raw`kg`,
          },
          {
            propertyAsLatex: String.raw`c_{w}`,
            value: "Specific heat capacity of the known substance in ",
            unitAsLatex: String.raw`J\cdot kg^{-1}\cdot K^{-1}`,
          },
          {
            propertyAsLatex: String.raw`\Delta T_{w}`,
            value: "Temperature change of known substance in",
            unitAsLatex: String.raw`K`,
          },
          {
            propertyAsLatex: String.raw`m_{s}`,
            value: "Mass of sodium chloride solution in",
            unitAsLatex: String.raw`kg`,
          },
          {
            propertyAsLatex: String.raw`\Delta T_{s}`,
            value: "Temperature change of sodium chloride solution in",
            unitAsLatex: String.raw`K`,
          },
        ]}
      />
      <h2>Hypothesis</h2>
      <p>
        Equation 3 states an inverse proportionality between the specific heat
        capacity of the solution and the mass of the solution. However, this
        proportionality is invalid. A proportionality derived from an equation
        must be able to be represented as a linear function, where all other
        variables are distilled into a gradient constant. The other variables in
        this equation are expected to not be constant, so proportionality cannot
        be assumed.
      </p>
      <p>
        Sodium chloride has a specific heat capacity of <InlineMath
          latex={String.raw`864 J \cdot kg^{−1} \cdot K^{−1}`}
        /> (Chase 1998). Given this value, it is clear that dissolving sodium chloride
        in water would lower its specific heat capacity. The proportionality between
        the mass of sodium chloride and water would not be direct since the Y-intercept
        is expected to be the specific heat capacity of water, <InlineMath
          latex={String.raw`4186 J \cdot kg^{−1} \cdot K^{−1}`}
        /> (Engineering Toolbox n.d.). It is difficult to predict the type of correlation
        that exists between the two variables since no known equation accurately
        relates the two with a constant. The domain of this graph would be from 0
        kilograms to the saturation point for water and salt. Beyond the saturation
        point, we may reasonably assume different behaviour since the material is
        no longer a liquid and will have different properties.
      </p>
