      <p>
        Equation 3 has two components, the first, in blue, is the energy
        transferred to the distilled water that was already in the calorimeter.
        Since we measured the mass of this water to be 150ml, we will use that
        value for <InlineMath latex={String.raw`m_{w}`} />. For <InlineMath
          latex={String.raw`c_{w}`}
        />, we are using distilled water, so we will use the textbook value for
        water's specific heat capacity, <InlineMath
          latex={String.raw`4186 \:kg J\cdot kg^{-1}\cdot K^{-1}`}
        /> (Engineering Toolbox n.d.). We measured the temperature of the distilled
        water before adding the sodium chloride solution and the temperature after
        adding the sodium chloride solution, we can use these values to calculate
        a temperature delta, <InlineMath latex={String.raw`\Delta T_{w}`} />.
      </p>
      <p>
        For the second component (in red), the mass of the solution (<InlineMath
          latex={String.raw`m_{s}`}
        />) is calculated by subtracting the mass of the distilled water
        (0.15kg) from the measured mass of the combined solution. This way, any
        solution that evaporated is accounted for. The temperature delta (<InlineMath
          latex={String.raw`\Delta T_{s}`}
        />) for this component is calculated similarly, except the initial
        temperature value is 363 K since that is the temperature we heated the
        solution to.
      </p>
