      <p>
        The Y-intercept of the line of best fit represents the specific heat
        capacity of distilled water. The expected Y-intercept is <InlineMath
          latex={String.raw`4186 \: J\cdot kg^{-1}\cdot K^{-1}`}
        />, so our Y-intercept is relatively accurate.
      </p>
      <p>
        The gradient of the line of best fit has the units <InlineMath
        latex={String.raw`J\cdot kg^{-1}\cdot K^{-1} \cdot kg^{-1}`}
      />. This is the specific heat capacity per kilogram of salt.
      </p>
      <p>
        Figure 2 shows a negative, linear correlation. The points on the graph
        lie close to the trendline and the trendline passes through all the
        error bars. Some points, like the last 2, deviate further from the
        trendline. This error does not appear to be systematic and is likely
        random. The trendline passes through the error bars of these points, and
        there are no other reasonable grounds to remove them.
      </p>
      <p>
        Figure 2 also features minimum and maximum lines of best fit, both of
        which pass through all the error bars. The minimum and maximum lines of
        best fit are used to calculate uncertainty in the gradient.
      </p>
      <p>
        The gradient has a reasonable, but not inconsiderable uncertainty. This
        indicates that there are some issues with precision in this data that
        could be improved.
      </p>
      <p>
        The accuracy of the collected data could be considered to be good since
        it is within the expected order of magnitude based on literature values
        for specific heat capacity (Engineering Toolbox n.d.). The control trial
        of 0 grams of sodium chloride measured a specific heat capacity of <InlineMath
          latex={String.raw`4274 \cdot kg^{−1} \cdot K^{−1}`}
        />, which is within 3% of the literature value, <InlineMath
          latex={String.raw`4186 \cdot kg^{−1} \cdot K^{−1}`}
        />.
      </p>
      <p>
        The evidence gathered in this experiment supports the mass of sodium
        chloride dissolved in distilled water being proportional to the inverse
        of specific heat capacity of that solution.
      </p>
      <p>
        Specific heat capacity and sodium chloride have applications and
        implications. Ocean Thermal Energy Conversion is a process where the
        warm surface of the ocean is used to vaporise a substance of low boiling
        point which spins a turbine (Lynn et al. 2018). Ocean Thermal Energy
        Conversion is currently a process with only 3-5% efficiency, so there is
        potential for great improvements. It was found in a 2018 study that as
        the specific heat capacity of the water decreased due to salt content,
        the amount of electricity generated per unit temperature decreased in
        these systems.
      </p>
      <h2>Evaluation</h2>
      <p>
        The design and method of this investigation were suitable for reaching a
        viable conclusion. However, the experiment experienced some systematic
        and random error that impacted the accuracy and precision of the data.
      </p>
